{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17041"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17041"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.04,0.21,0.08,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5301"},{"type":"tags","id":"7631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22906"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColchicine is an ancient medicine derived from the autumn crocus plant that remains an important treatment for gout and other inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of colchicine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds to tubulin and prevents microtubule formation","Stabilises lysosomal membranes","Increases uric acid excretion","Blocks prostaglandin synthesis","Inhibits xanthine oxidase"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding to tubulin and preventing microtubule formation\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of colchicine. By binding to tubulin dimers, colchicine prevents their polymerisation into microtubules. By inhibiting microtubule polymerisation, colchicine disrupts cytoskeletal function in inflammatory cells, particularly neutrophils. This reduces their migration, adhesion, and release of inflammatory mediators\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilising lysosomal membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant mechanism of colchicine and would not explain its anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing uric acid excretion\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of uricosuric drugs like probenecid, which are used for long-term gout prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, which work through a different anti-inflammatory pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting xanthine oxidase\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of allopurinol and febuxostat, which are used to prevent gout attacks by reducing uric acid production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing microtubule formation, colchicine inhibits neutrophil migration, phagocytosis, and degranulation. This reduces inflammation in conditions like gout without directly affecting uric acid metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["",""